Update shared_pointer.hpp

Name correction: decrement_n_destroy() to decrement_and_destroy().
There's no decrement_n_destroy(), only decrement_and_destroy() is found.

Fix the answer to exercise 5.13

ix under case "1" is not initialized, UB will happen. 
So bring the definition of ix out of switch statement.

I think this should be better.

Update ex10_20_21.cpp

exercise 10.21: check_and_decrement no longer decrements values <= 0 and only returns true for 0.

Update ex4_22.cpp

Adding the conditional operator part of the exercise

Update ex7_22.h

While the original (using 'struct') was technically correct, I believe using 'class' makes more sense here.  Here's what the book states: 
"As a matter of programming style, when we define a class intending for all of its
members to be public, we use struct. If we intend to have private members,
then we use class."

Update ex6_47.cpp

You only want to print debugging information when debugging is NOT disabled (in other words, when NDEBUG is not defined; NDEBUG stands for No Debugging).  The original version was doing the opposite (printing vector size when debugging was disabled).

Update README.md

Changed 'preexisted' to 'preexisting'.  It's what the book states as well in a Tip a few pages earlier.

Fix ex6_21

The original solution would allow you to modify the pointer itself inside larger_one function.  Applying a 2nd const ensures that the function can't modify the address stored in 'p' pointer.

Update README.md

Added a slightly more descriptive comments to exercise 5.13 part c

Update ex13_28.h

Please refer to: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/615355/is-there-any-reason-to-check-for-a-null-pointer-before-deleting
First, I don't think we need to check nullptr before delete, because we are not overloading delete. delete will check if the pointer is NULL for you, so it is safe to delete a null pointer.
Second, setting the pointer to nullptr after deleting it may be good sometimes, but it really doesn't look necessary in our case since the entire TreeNode object will be destroyed anyways and there is no way we can reuse the members.

Update ex5_14.cpp

In the previous version, when you successively input same strings, then end the loop by ctrl+z(windows), the result is no duplicated words, which is not accord with our input.(eg. input three "123" and then ended with ctrl+z). 
The reason is that if the inputs are same from start, we will never enter the else branch where assign value to variable 'max_duplicated'.
So the operation on 'max_duplicated' should be done only when the 'count > max_duplicated.second + 1', which shows that continously duplicated inputs are tested. And when the input is not same with the previous, we should set the count for the new string to 1.
